english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of Kandong Seon Temple
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gyeongwon lies in Yangguang Province, the most remote county of the region. Yet from Chamberlain Zhang Hegy onward, illustrious scholars and noble officials have emerged in abundance—for the land itself, where mountains and rivers interweave and the seas embrace distant shores, channels a force most extraordinary, and exhales a spirit most refined.

    Five miles to the northwest of the county, a mountain rises abruptly, opening wide its mouth. Within lies the foundation of an ancient temple, which the local people have long called Kandong—truly the most wondrous and sublime spot in all the county.

    There is a man named Ha Won-seo, a cavalry guard of the imperial court, descended from the gentry of this very place. In his youth he served at court, earning a reputation for conscientiousness and sincerity. Once, while hunting, he came upon this place and beheld crumbling walls and broken foundations swallowed by grass and vines. Moved with profound sorrow, he took an oath in his heart to restore this abandoned temple. It was the year Gapjin of the Yuan Dynasty's Dade era.

    For more than twenty years since then, he has exhausted his purse, rationed his food and clothing, and poured every resource into this work. He felled timber from the forest and quarried stone from the mountainside. Laying gravel and spreading earth, he labored alongside his workers, never content until every detail matched his vision, revising and perfecting again and again, showing not the slightest weariness.

    The pillars shine red with vermillion, and the decorated beams stand bold and magnificent—these are the halls where the Buddha dwells. The chambers are warm and spacious—these are where the monks make their dwelling. He raised the great hall high and widened the galleries, so that sheer peaks seem grasped through the windows and broad waters appear at the courtyard gate. Layer upon layer of walls encircle the grounds, and green pines stand in perfect rows. Ascending and descending, gazing left and right, all is in harmony.

    The bells and drums for chanting are without flaw, the cauldrons for cooking are complete, the cushions and mats for sitting and resting lack nothing. He gathered servants to attend to every need. In all these matters, not a single detail has been overlooked.

    When he pierced the rock to tap a cold spring, the labor of drawing water ceased. When he cultivated barren land into fertile fields, provisions for the monks became abundant. It was as though the spirits themselves, moved by such sincerity, came forth to aid him.

    This very autumn, the Zen master Jigong from the Western lands passed through on his way to Mount Hua. Upon witnessing this place, he uttered great praises, saying such a work was rarely seen. When he departed, he remained with hundreds upon hundreds of his disciples.

    A visitor once asked Ikjae, "In ancient times, the Xiao clan of Liang wielded the power of ten thousand chariots and exhausted the resources of all lands to build towers and temples beyond counting. Would not their merit exceed that of Ha's single temple a hundredfold? Yet Bodhidharma criticized such works, while Jigong praised Ha's. Why this difference?"

    Ikjae replied: "There are deeds that wear the same outward form yet harbor different principles within. Only one with true discernment can distinguish between them. The ancient sages possessed all under heaven yet claimed nothing as their own, for they knew it was not theirs to possess. To build merit from what one does not truly own is less meritorious than not building at all. I observe in Ha a different truth: his exertion draws only from his own resources, borrowing nothing from others; his intention serves the welfare of others, not himself. Therefore, a stone no larger than a fist and a handful of earth become merit towering higher than Mount Sumeru, and a thread of incense smoke and a candle's light become benefit broader than the sands of the Ganges. This is the distinction between deeds that appear the same yet differ in essence. As for the agreement and disagreement between Jigong and Bodhidharma, speak to me again when your eye has grown keener."
  footnotes:
    - 'Chamberlain Zhang Hegy (章和公): A notable historical figure from the region mentioned to establish the area''s tradition of producing talented individuals.'
    - 'Dade era (大德): A reign period of the Yuan Dynasty (1297-1307), placing this work in the early 14th century.'
    - 'Bodhidharma''s criticism: Reference to the classical Buddhist teaching that merit accumulated through displays of power and state resources may lack true spiritual value.'
    - 'Ikjae (益齋): The author''s pen name; Lee Je-hyeon also went by Ikjae.'
    - 'Mount Sumeru and sands of the Ganges: Traditional Buddhist metaphors for immeasurable height and quantity, emphasizing that true merit transcends material measurement.'
